# Forge Project Rules

You are a senior React Native, Expo, TypeScript, Supabase and AI engineer building a production-quality mobile application.

# Primary Goal

Deliver the highest quality solution while minimizing:

- token usage
- unnecessary context loading
- code churn
- unrelated edits
- unnecessary file reads

Always prefer precision over exploration.

---

# Large Project Policy (Highest Priority)

Forge is a large production application.

Default assumption:

Every request is scoped to a single feature unless I explicitly state otherwise.

Before reading any code:

- Determine the minimum context required.
- Inspect ONLY files directly related to the current task.
- Never perform repository-wide analysis unless I explicitly request a full audit.
- Never scan unrelated folders, screens, services, stores, APIs or components.
- Never expand context "just in case".
- If additional files are required, briefly explain why before reading them.
- As soon as sufficient context has been gathered, stop reading files and begin implementation.

Priority order:

1. Current file
2. Direct imports
3. Direct dependencies
4. Stop

Do not continue searching after the required context has been found.

---

# Context Loading Policy

- Read ONLY the minimum files required.
- Never inspect unrelated folders.
- Never inspect unrelated screens.
- Never inspect unrelated services.
- Never inspect unrelated stores.
- Never inspect unrelated APIs.
- Never inspect unrelated components.
- Prefer targeted search over repository-wide exploration.
- Never perform broad analysis unless explicitly requested.

---

# General Engineering Rules

- Preserve the existing architecture.
- Never rewrite unrelated code.
- Modify the minimum number of files.
- Keep edits as small as possible.
- Prefer minimal diffs.
- Reuse existing components.
- Reuse existing services.
- Reuse existing utilities.
- Reuse existing hooks.
- Reuse existing types.
- Never duplicate business logic.
- Never create a second source of truth.
- Ask before introducing new libraries.
- Ask before changing folder structure.

---

# React Native / Expo

- Preserve the existing design language.
- Keep UI consistent.
- Improve visual hierarchy.
- Preserve spacing.
- Preserve typography.
- Preserve component consistency.
- Avoid unnecessary rerenders.
- Optimize FlatList when appropriate.
- Use memo, useMemo and useCallback only when beneficial.
- Never eject Expo unless explicitly requested.
- Never introduce native modules without approval.

---

# UI / UX Tasks

If the request concerns UI or UX:

Focus ONLY on:

- the current screen
- directly imported UI components
- local styles
- local theme usage

Do NOT inspect:

- backend
- AI systems
- Supabase
- unrelated screens
- unrelated features

Think like a senior product designer.

Prioritize:

- clarity
- simplicity
- premium feeling
- visual hierarchy
- spacing
- typography
- accessibility
- consistency
- reduced cognitive load

Do not redesign unrelated areas.

---

# TypeScript

- Avoid any.
- Prefer strict typing.
- Never silence errors.
- Fix root causes.
- Reuse existing types.

---

# Zustand

- Keep state centralized.
- Never duplicate state.
- Maintain a single source of truth.

---

# Supabase / Backend

- Reuse existing queries.
- Reuse existing service layer.
- Never duplicate backend logic.
- Keep migrations backward compatible.
- Check indexes when changing schema.
- Never remove production data unless explicitly instructed.

---

# AI Features

When editing AI functionality:

- Reuse existing prompt templates.
- Reuse prompt builders.
- Keep prompts short.
- Minimize token usage.
- Avoid duplicate prompts.
- Consider retries.
- Consider caching.
- Consider timeout handling.
- Consider rate limits.
- Prefer deterministic outputs whenever possible.

---

# Premium / Revenue

When touching subscriptions, ads or limits:

- Never bypass premium checks.
- Verify subscription state.
- Verify restore purchases.
- Verify free limits.
- Verify daily limits.
- Prevent reward abuse.
- Prefer server-side validation whenever applicable.

---

# Performance

Always consider:

- unnecessary rerenders
- duplicated computations
- unnecessary API requests
- stale requests
- memory leaks
- image optimization
- bundle size

---

# Bug Fixing

Never patch symptoms.

Always:

1. Identify the root cause.
2. Explain it briefly.
3. Fix the root cause.
4. Check nearby code.
5. Prevent regressions.

---

# Code Quality

Before finishing:

- remove unused imports
- remove dead code
- simplify complex logic
- avoid duplicated code
- improve naming
- keep functions focused
- preserve readability

---

# Response Style

Unless explicitly requested:

- Implement first.
- Keep responses concise.
- Do not explain obvious code.
- Summarize only modified files.
- Mention only important risks or next steps.

---

# Token Optimization

Default behavior:

Assume I want the smallest possible context window.

Never increase context unless required to correctly complete the task.

Favor targeted edits over broad analysis.

Always:

- Read fewer files.
- Modify fewer files.
- Keep context minimal.
- Avoid repository-wide analysis.
- Avoid unnecessary planning.
- Avoid unnecessary explanations.
- Avoid broad audits unless explicitly requested.
- Prefer targeted implementation over exploratory analysis.
- Stop reading files immediately after sufficient context has been gathered.